description: From Middle English sty, from Old English stī, stiġ (“sty, pen, a wooden enclosure; hall”, chiefly in compounds), from Proto-Germanic *stiją. Cognate with German Stiege (“wooden crate”), dialectal German Steige (“hen-coop”), Danish sti (“sty, enclosure for swine, sheep, hens, etc.”), Swedish stia (“sty for pigs, geese, etc.”), Norwegian sti (“flock of sheep”), Icelandic stía (“a kennel”).

entries.meaning: A pen or enclosure for swine.
(figurative) A messy, dirty or debauched place.

verbs.description: sty (third-person singular simple present sties, present participle stying, simple past and past participle stied)

entries.meaning: To place in, or as if in, a sty
To live in a sty, or any messy or dirty place

description: From Middle English stien, stiȝen, stighen, from Old English stīgan (“to go; ascend, mount”), from Proto-West Germanic *stīgan, from Proto-Germanic *stīganą, from Proto-Indo-European *steygʰ-. Cognate with Dutch stijgen, German steigen, Danish stige, Norwegian Bokmål stige, Norwegian Nynorsk and Swedish stiga, Old Norse stíga.

verbs.description: sty (third-person singular simple present sties, present participle stying, simple past and past participle stied)

entries.meaning: (obsolete) To ascend, rise up, climb. [9th–17th c.]
examples: From this lower tract he dared to stie up to the clowdes.

description: From Middle English styanye, mistaken as "sty on eye" yet composed of Old English stīġend (“sty”, literally “riser”), agent noun from stīgan (“to rise”) + Middle English yë (“eye”).
